    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="239"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d239">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/1051.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Chinese Government is reported to have signed a preliminary agreement for a
                    loan of £10,000,000 secured on the salt gabelle, with Lloyd’s Bank and Union of
                    London and Smith’s Bank.<note n="2" xml:id="d239fn2">This is later known as “the
                        Crisp loan” (C. Birch Crisp &amp; Co.); references to it occur at <ref
                            target="#pg_152">pp. 152</ref>, <ref target="#pg_153">153</ref> and
                        later; officially it was “The Chinese Government 5 per cent Gold Loan of
                        1912.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
